<html>
 <head>
 </head>
 <body>
  <h1>
   Time Source Units
  </h1>
  <table>
   <colgroup>
    <col/>
    <col/>
    <col/>
   </colgroup>
   <tbody>
    <tr>
     <th>
      <span>
       <a href="../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Reference/Time_Sources/Time_Source_Units.htm">
        Time Source Unit Constant
       </a>
      </span>
     </th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <th>
      Constant
     </th>
     <th>
      Description
     </th>
     <th>
      Value
     </th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      <span>
       time_source_units_seconds
      </span>
     </td>
     <td>
      Use seconds for the
      <span>
       Time Source
      </span>
      period (frame-independent)
     </td>
     <td>
      0
     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      <span>
       time_source_units_frames
      </span>
     </td>
     <td>
      Use frames for the
      <span>
       Time Source
      </span>
      period (frame-dependent)
     </td>
     <td>
      1
     </td>
    </tr>
   </tbody>
  </table>
  These constants are used in
  <a href="time_source_create.htm">
   <span>
    time_source_create()
   </span>
  </a>
  and
  <a href="time_source_reconfigure.htm">
   <span>
    time_source_reconfigure()
   </span>
  </a>
  to set the units used for the
  <span>
   Time Source
  </span>
  's period, and are returned by
  <a href="time_source_get_units.htm">
   <span>
    time_source_get_units()
   </span>
  </a>
  .
   
   
    If you use seconds, your
  <span>
   Time Source
  </span>
  will run independently from the game's framerate.
   
   
    If you use frames, your
  <span>
   Time Source
  </span>
  will be dependent on the game's framerate.
   
   
    You can also use BPM (beats-per-minute) as a unit by calling
  <a href="time_bpm_to_seconds.htm">
   <span>
    time_bpm_to_seconds()
   </span>
  </a>
  to convert your BPM value to a period in seconds, and then using
  <span>
   time_source_units_seconds
  </span>
  as the unit.
 </body>
</html>